==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proselyte
<hw>Pros"e*lyte</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>proselite</ets>, OF. <ets>proselite</ets>, F.
<ets>proselytus</ets>, Gr. <?/, adj., that has come, n., a new comer,
especially, one who has come over from heathenism to the Jewish
religion; <?/ toward, to + (prob.) the root of <?/ to come.]</ety>
<def>A new convert especially a convert to some religion or religious
sect, or to some particular opinion, system, or party; thus, a Gentile
converted to Judaism, or a pagan converted to Christianity, is a
<xex>proselyte</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye [Scribes and Pharisees] compass sea and land to make one
<qex>proselyte</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xxiii. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fresh confidence the speculatist takes⟦br⟧
From every harebrained <qex>proselyte</qex> he makes.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Convert</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proselyte</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Proselyte
<hw>Pros"e*lyte</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Proselyted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Proselyting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To convert to some religion,
opinion, or system; to bring over.</def><-- se proselytize -->
<rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proselytism</ent>⟦br⟧
